    "content": "# CloudWatch\n\n    ## What it is\n    CloudWatch is AWS observability for logs, metrics, alarms, dashboards, Logs Insights, metric filters, alarm actions, and production debugging. This note is written for interview preparation and production implementation, so it covers the service mental model, setup path, IAM/security, scaling, failure behavior, monitoring, and comparison with related services.\n\n    ## Why it exists\n    CloudWatch exists because production systems need a managed building block instead of re-implementing the same infrastructure repeatedly. The important interview skill is not only naming the service, but explaining the workload shape where it is the right tool and the workload shape where it becomes the wrong tool.\n\n    ## Mental model\n    Think of CloudWatch as a boundary in your architecture. It accepts input, applies its own rules and limits, integrates with IAM and CloudWatch, and then hands control to the next service or consumer. In design discussions, always identify producer, consumer, failure path, retry path, and monitoring signal.\n\n    ## Core concepts\n    | Concept | Production meaning |\n    |---|---|\n    | Log group | Container for logs |\n| Log stream | Source stream |\n| Metric | Time-series signal |\n| Alarm | Threshold/evaluation |\n| Dashboard | Visual health view |\n| Logs Insights | Query engine |\n| Metric filter | Metric from logs |\n\n    ## Flow diagram\n    ```mermaid\n    flowchart TD\n  A[Lambda/ECS/API/RDS] --> B[CloudWatch Logs]\n  A --> C[CloudWatch Metrics]\n  B --> D[Logs Insights]\n  C --> E[Alarm]\n  E --> F[SNS notification]\n  C --> G[Dashboard]\n    ```\n\n    ## Setup from console\n    1. Open CloudWatch\n2. Open log groups\n3. Set log retention\n4. Run Logs Insights query\n5. Find service metrics\n6. Create alarm\n7. Attach SNS action\n8. Create dashboard\n9. Review alarms/runbook\n\n    ## CLI or SDK example\n    ```sql\n    fields @timestamp, @message\n| filter @message like /ERROR/\n| sort @timestamp desc\n| limit 50\n    ```\n\n    ## Security and IAM permissions\n    Use least privilege. Give the calling identity only the exact actions and resources it needs. For AWS services, prefer IAM roles over access keys. For cross-service invocation, remember that the caller may need an identity policy while the target may also need a resource policy. If encryption uses KMS, the KMS key policy must allow the same access path.\n\n    ## Networking and VPC considerations\n    Ask whether the service is public, private, VPC-attached, or accessed through endpoints. For private workloads, keep compute in private subnets, expose traffic through API Gateway or ALB, and restrict security groups to known callers.\n\n    ## Retry and failure behavior\n    Decide what happens when the downstream service fails. For event-driven flows, use retries, DLQs, idempotency keys, deterministic output paths, and failure records. For synchronous APIs, return clear status codes and avoid hiding long-running processing inside a single request.\n\n    ## Scaling behavior\n    Scaling depends on the service. Serverless services scale by managed concurrency/capacity, queues absorb bursts, databases scale around partition/index/connection limits, and containers scale by replicas/tasks/pods. Always include the bottleneck: database connections, hot partitions, queue age, target health, or worker runtime.\n\n    ## Monitoring and debugging\n    Use CloudWatch logs, metrics, alarms, and structured correlation IDs. Debug by verifying IAM permissions, event payload shape, region/account, resource ARNs, networking, KMS permissions, and target health.\n\n    ## Cost mental model\n    Cost usually comes from requests, storage, compute duration, data transfer, provisioned capacity, logs, and retries. Production designs should clean up old data, avoid noisy logs, and avoid retry storms.\n\n    ## Common mistakes\n    - Choosing CloudWatch because it is familiar rather than because the workload matches it.\n    - Forgetting IAM or resource-based permissions.\n    - Missing DLQ/retry/idempotency for async processing.\n    - Ignoring CloudWatch metrics until production fails.\n    - Putting large payloads in events instead of storing data in S3 and sending references.\n    - Not documenting when the service should not be used.\n\n    ## When to use\n    Use CloudWatch when its managed behavior matches the problem: durability, routing, queueing, orchestration, compute, relational querying, NoSQL access, ETL, or observability depending on the service.\n\n    ## When not to use\n    Do not use CloudWatch as a universal hammer. If you need strict relational joins, use RDS/Aurora. If you need durable work buffering, use SQS. If you need orchestration, use Step Functions. If you need long-running compute, use ECS/Glue/Batch instead of forcing Lambda.\n\n    ## Comparison with alternatives\n    CloudWatch vs X-Ray: CloudWatch logs/metrics/alarms; X-Ray distributed tracing/service map.\n\n    ## Interview explanation\n    In an interview, explain CloudWatch in four sentences: what it is, why it exists, the exact production scenario where you would use it, and the exact scenario where you would not use it. Then mention IAM, retry/failure path, monitoring, and cost.\n\n    ## Production observability\nUse structured logs with request IDs. Watch Lambda errors/throttles, SQS queue age, ECS CPU/memory/target health, API 5xx/latency, RDS connections/CPU, Step Functions failures.\n\n    ## Production checklist\n    - Least-privilege IAM is defined.\n    - Encryption and secret handling are configured.\n    - Retry, DLQ, or failure destination exists where applicable.\n    - CloudWatch logs/metrics/alarms exist.\n    - Cost cleanup/lifecycle/retention is configured.\n    - Terraform or IaC exists for repeatability.\n    - Runbook exists for common failures.\n"
